english:
  title: A Refutation of Buddhist Compassion
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth make the generation of all things their heart. Humans, born from this generative heart of heaven and earth, thereby possess it. Thus all people share the heart of compassion for others—this is what we call benevolence. Though the Buddha came from foreign lands, he too belonged to humankind. How could he alone lack this heart? What we Confucians call the stirring of compassion and what the Buddhists call loving-kindness are both expressions of benevolence. Though their words are similar, the methods by which they practice are vastly different.

    Parents share our vital essence; other humans share our kind; all things share our origin of life. Thus benevolence flows outward from the nearest to us—parents, then to other people, then to all creatures—like water filling one depression before reaching the next and the next. When the source runs deep, its influence travels far. All things under heaven rest within the embrace of my benevolent love. Therefore it is said: first perfect filial love, then extend benevolence to the people, then extend compassion to all creatures. This is the way of the Confucian sage—unified, authentic, and continuous.

    But the Buddhists are not so. Toward animals—whether fierce as wolves and tigers or insignificant as mosquitoes and gnats—they willingly offer their own flesh without hesitation. Toward people, whether from Yue or Qin, they wish to share their food with the hungry and their garments with the cold. This is what they call almsgiving. Yet toward those closest to us—parents and children—and those most worthy of reverence—sovereigns and ministers—they wish to sever all bonds. What purpose lies in this?

    People conduct themselves with care because they have parents, spouses, and children to support. But Buddhists regard human relationships as false illusions. Children need not honor fathers; ministers need not respect sovereigns. They treat the closest kin as strangers and the most worthy of respect as trifles. Having lost this root, their compassion becomes like a tree without roots, water without source—it easily runs dry and brings no true benefit to people or things. They unsheathe their swords to slay serpents without a moment's hesitation, yet speak of hell's torments with utmost cruelty. They who lack such gentleness—where is their compassion now?

    Yet the innate nature of this heart cannot be completely obscured. Even in the most darkened soul, at the sight of parents, filial love and affection spontaneously arise. Why then do they not turn back and seek this truth? Instead they say, "The habits of past lives have not yet been fully purged; therefore the roots of attachment remain." There is no deeper delusion than this refusal to awaken. This is why the Buddhist teaching contains neither righteousness nor principle, and why it cannot be accepted within the sphere of civilized learning.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yue and Qin: Ancient Chinese states used here to represent geographical and cultural differences, emphasizing the universal scope of Buddhist compassion across boundaries.'
    - The analogy of water filling successive depressions illustrates the Confucian concept of graduated love, where benevolence extends naturally from the nearest relationships outward.
    - The reference to habits of past lives (習氣) reflects the Buddhist doctrine of karma and reincarnation, which Jeong Do-jeon criticizes as a rationalization for contradictions in Buddhist ethics.
